[{"id":"VH949099","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH949090.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">An electron is released from rest at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>M</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Which of the following vectors indicates the direction of the electronâ€™s initial acceleration?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH949099_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents two small spheres in the x y coordinate plane with the origin labeled O. The first sphere has a charge of positive q and is located on the x axis, at a distance of d to the left of the origin. The second sphere has a charge of negative q and is located on the x axis, at a distance of d to the right of the origin. Two points, labeled M and N, are shown on the graph. Point N is located on the x axis, at a distance of d to the right of the sphere with a charge of negative q. Point M is located near the top of the y axis above the origin.\" height=\"179\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH949090.g07.png\" width=\"400\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"passage_para\">An electric dipole consists of two small spheres which carry charges of equal magnitude <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"q\"><math alttext=\"q\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>q</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and opposite signs as shown in the figure above. The center of the dipole is at the origin. Two labeled points <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>M</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"N\"><math alttext=\"N\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>N</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> are on the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"y\"><math alttext=\"y\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>-axis and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>-axis, respectively.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The direction will be undefined, because the electron will remain at rest.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"inline_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a vector pointing to the left.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH949099.g01.png\"/></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"inline_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a vector pointing to the right.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH949099.g02.png\"/></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"inline_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a vector pointing upward.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH949099.g03.png\"/></span></p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"inline_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a vector pointing downward.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH949099.g04.png\"/></span></p>"],"answer":1}]